## Principle

This is AP-066 — **Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text** — now amended with its full mechanical explanation and codified priority rule.

The underlying principle, stated for the record:

> **`flex-shrink: 0` on the protected element is necessary but not sufficient. The compressible sibling must also carry `flex: 1 1 0` to set its basis to zero — only then does the browser distribute space from scratch, guaranteeing the rigid element is placed first and the remainder given to the yielding side.** Belt (`flex-shrink: 0`) and suspenders (`white-space: nowrap`) on the identity element. `flex: 1 1 0` + `min-width: 0` on the compressible element. These four properties work as a system; any one missing and the guarantee breaks.

The priority hierarchy is now codified as Class 1 (identity — never wraps, ever, at any viewport) vs Class 2 (ancillary nav content — wraps to a bounded number of lines). The tagline wrapping to two lines is by design. The logo wrapping is never acceptable — and the SCSS now structurally enforces that, not accidentally achieves it.
